Smart Contract Platform assets are designed for the building of decentralized applications, layer 2 scaling solutions,(DAOs), and other custom protocols.

Decentralized finance (DeFi) is an emerging financial technology utilizing the secure distributed ledgers of the blockchain.
What it does:
DeFi circumvents the fees and barriers that traditional financial institutions implement for using their services, providing users self-sovereignty and direct access.
Why it matters:
DeFi holds the potential to bring about an egalitarian financial system, as anyone with an internet connection can leverage DeFi services.
Use cases:

DeFi platforms focus primarily on providing borrowing, lending, staking and exchange services, whereby participants can deposit funds as collateral via decentralized smart contracts. As such, one of the key aspects of DeFi is total value locked (TVL). TVL is the total value of all assets deposited, or staked, in a decentralized finance protocol that generate economic activity.

The CoinDesk Chainlink Price Index (LNX) provides a USD-denominated reference rate for the spot price of Chainlink (LINK). The index leverages real-time prices from multiple constituent exchanges to provide a representative spot price. Each constituent exchange is weighted proportionally to its trailing 24-hour liquidity with adjustments for price variance and inactivity.

Given the potential for anomalies or manipulation at individual exchanges, constituent weights may dynamically adjust using CoinDesk Indices proprietary Constituent Weighting Adjustment Algorithm (CWAA). The algorithm is designed to calculate a real-time index that is an accurate and reliable reflection of the market price of each digital asset, using multi-sourced spot prices and dynamically reduce the weights of individual exchanges with lower liquidity, inactivity, and higher price variance.

Decentralized finance (DeFi) is an emerging financial technology utilizing the secure distributed ledgers of the blockchain.
What it does:
DeFi circumvents the fees and barriers that traditional financial institutions implement for using their services, providing users self-sovereignty and direct access.
Why it matters:
DeFi holds the potential to bring about an egalitarian financial system, as anyone with an internet connection can leverage DeFi services.
Use cases:

DeFi platforms focus primarily on providing borrowing, lending, staking and exchange services, whereby participants can deposit funds as collateral via decentralized smart contracts. As such, one of the key aspects of DeFi is total value locked (TVL). TVL is the total value of all assets deposited, or staked, in a decentralized finance protocol that generate economic activity.
